sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1154006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Mating pheromone-induced IGPD and constitutive LDH expression in yeast
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Adam Nighswander, Tanner Reeb and Bianca Maled

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LDHA
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Subunit A of L-lactate-specific dehydrogenase (M-isozyme) catalyzes the interconversion of pyruvate plus NADH and L-lactate plus NAD in the final step of anaerobic glycolysis.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Adam Nighswander, Tanner Reeb and Bianca Maled
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Synthetic coding sequence is derived from the polypeptide sequence of Homo sapiens lactate dehydrogenase subunit A.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The sequence is optimized for high codon bias in yeast and conformity with current BioBrick standards.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: TEF2 pr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Saccharomyces cerevisiae constitutive TEF2 promoter variant
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Constitutive TEF2 promoter variant. This variant has six additional nucleotides (tactag) at the 3' terminus of part BBa_K165037.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Adam Nighswander, Tanner Reeb and Bianca Maled

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: IGPD
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The Saccharomyces cerevisiae HIS3 gene encodes imidazoleglycerol-phosphate dehydratase (IGPD), which catalyzes the interconversion of D-erythro-1-(imidazol-4-yl)glycerol 3-phosphate and 3-(imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropyl phosphate plus H2O. The dehydration reaction is a key step in the biosynthesis of histidine in many bacteria, fungi and plants. The gene is routinely used as a selectable marker in yeast histidine auxotrophs harboring a genomic his3 mutation (e.g., his3-delta1). Although, it also compliments Escherichia coli hisB mutations (e.g., ΔhisB720::kan).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Adam Nighswander, Tanner Reeb and Bianca Maled
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Coding sequence is from the HIS3/YOR202W locus on yeast chromosome XV from coordinates 721946 to 722608.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: FUS1 pr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Saccharomyces cerevisiae FUS1 promoter (induced by mating pheromone)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The FUS1 promoter is induced by Ste12, which is a key regulatory factor in the yeast mating pheromone response pathway. The promoter contains three copies of the Ste12 binding sequence. Genes driven by the promoter are induced when mating factor receptors on the cell's surface bind mating factor secreted by cells of the opposite mating type.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Adam Nighswander, Tanner Reeb and Bianca Maled
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The sequence is from the yeast genome (McCaffrey G, Clay FJ, Kelsay K, and Sprague GF Jr (1987) Identification and regulation of a gene required for cell fusion during mating of the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae. Mol. Cell. Biol. 7 (8), 2680-2690).
